Because it enables them to make money off of their ownership part in the firm, a liquidity event such as an initial public offering (IPO) or purchase may be regarded an exit for the original founder of a company even if that person is still actively operating the business. This indicates that they are able to transform their stock into cash, which may provide them financial stability as well as the opportunity to seek other business opportunities. A liquidity event not only represents an important milestone in the growth and development of the firm, but it may also indicate a change in the organization's overall direction and the priorities it places its focus on. Overall, a liquidity event can be seen as an exit for the original founder because it enables them to reap the rewards of their hard work and dedication while also opening up new opportunities and possibilities. This is because it allows them to reap the rewards of their hard work and dedication while also opening up new opportunities and possibilities. 